Interview Thinking Pattern 
Convert input → Adjacency List
Identify:
traversal? → BFS / DFS
shortest path? → BFS / Dijkstra
ordering? → Topo sort
grouping? → Union-Find
Use visited set ALWAYS

Final Mental Model
DFS = explore deeply
BFS = explore layer-wise
Heap = optimize choice (min/max)
Union-Find = grouping
Topo Sort = ordering with dependencies

What is a Graph?
A graph is a collection of nodes (vertices) and edges (connections)
Represent relationships between entities
Can be:
Directed (u → v)
Undirected (u ↔ v)
Weighted / Unweighted
Cyclic / Acyclic (DAG)

Graph Representations
1. Adjacency Matrix
2D matrix M[n][n]
M[u][v] = 1 → edge exists

Pros: O(1) edge lookup
Cons: Takes more space
Complexity:
Space: O(V²)
Edge check: O(1)
Iterate neighbors: O(V)

2. Adjacency List (Most used)
dict/list → node : [neighbors]

Pros:
Space efficient
Faster traversal
Complexity:
Space: O(V + E)
Edge check: O(deg(V))
Iterate neighbors: O(deg(V))

Graph Traversals
1. DFS (Depth First Search)
Go deep first
Recursive
Uses call stack
Iterative
Uses explicit stack
Complexity:
Time: O(V + E)
Space: O(V) (recursion/stack)

2. BFS (Breadth First Search)
Level-by-level traversal
Uses queue
Use case:
Shortest path (unweighted graph)
Complexity:
Time: O(V + E)
Space: O(V)

Key Graph Algorithms
1. Topological Sort (DAG only)
Ordering of nodes such that u → v comes before v
Approaches:
BFS (Kahn’s Algorithm)
DFS (postorder)

Complexity:
Time: O(V + E)
Space: O(V)


2. Shortest Path
Unweighted Graph:
BFS → O(V + E)

Weighted Graph:
Dijkstra (min heap)
Time: O((V + E) log V)
Space: O(V)

With Negative Weights:
Bellman-Ford
Time: O(V * E)
Space: O(V)


3. Cycle Detection
Directed Graph:
DFS + recursion stack
Undirected Graph:
DFS + parent tracking

Complexity:
Time: O(V + E)
Space: O(V)


4. Minimum Spanning Tree (MST)
Kruskal’s Algorithm:
Uses Union-Find
Time: O(E log E)

Prim’s Algorithm:
Uses min heap
Time: O(E log V)


5. Union-Find (Disjoint Set)
Used for:
Cycle detection
Connected components
Operations:
Find: O(α(N)) (almost constant)
Union: O(α(N))


Common Patterns
Visited / Seen set → avoid cycles
Graph = Tree + cycles + multiple paths
Always clarify:
Directed vs Undirected
Weighted vs Unweighted
Connected vs Disconnected


Applications of Graphs
Social networks (friends, followers)
Maps / GPS (shortest path)
Task scheduling (topological sort)
Network routing
Dependency resolution (build systems)
Recommendation systems
Web crawling



